snippet.textDisplay:
I mean "Intel move" is a bit harsh, you can put a Zen 2 chip in an A320 mobo, even though it's a different architecture. 
Intel has kept the same architecture since like 2015 and yet you have to buy new mobos every year to upgrade.
AMD's Zen 3 is a different architecture, it's probably going to need a new chipset to work with it.
If the pin laoyout is the same though, we might see BIOS updates for mobos equipped with older chipsets to make them compatible as was the case previously.
You want a significant performance increase and new features every year, you're bound to have to change your motherboard every so often. 
I bought a 1600 AF in january of this year, because I knew that Zen 3 wasn't too far away  and I knew I would probably have to buy a new motherboard to accomodate it, so I bought a used B350 for 40â‚¬.
Those who bought Zen 2 chips and B450/X570 motherboards will just wait for Zen4 to get a meaningful update I guess.
